<paragraph blockId="4.[810,1420,1216,1719]" pageId="4" pageNumber="327">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[810,972,1322,1346]" pageId="4" pageNumber="327">Identification.</emphasis>
This species is characterized by the following: basidiome perennial, effused-reflexed (
<figureCitation box="[1323,1408,1355,1380]" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="5.[168,231,1980,2000]" captionTargetBox="[168,1419,160,1956]" captionTargetId="figure-35@5.[168,1419,160,1956]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figure 3. Macroscopic structures (hymenophore, pileal region, pores of hymenophore, tubes and context). A. Fomitiporia langloisii. B. F. maxonii. C. F. murrillii. D. F. neotropica." pageId="4" pageNumber="327">Fig. 3A</figureCitation>
); hymenophoral surface with circular to angular pores, 6–7 per mm (
<figureCitation box="[961,1047,1422,1446]" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="5.[168,231,1980,2000]" captionTargetBox="[168,1419,160,1956]" captionTargetId="figure-35@5.[168,1419,160,1956]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figure 3. Macroscopic structures (hymenophore, pileal region, pores of hymenophore, tubes and context). A. Fomitiporia langloisii. B. F. maxonii. C. F. murrillii. D. F. neotropica." pageId="4" pageNumber="327">Fig. 3A</figureCitation>
); context homogeneous, thin, yellowish brown (
<figureCitation box="[969,1051,1456,1480]" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="5.[168,231,1980,2000]" captionTargetBox="[168,1419,160,1956]" captionTargetId="figure-35@5.[168,1419,160,1956]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figure 3. Macroscopic structures (hymenophore, pileal region, pores of hymenophore, tubes and context). A. Fomitiporia langloisii. B. F. maxonii. C. F. murrillii. D. F. neotropica." pageId="4" pageNumber="327">Fig. 3A</figureCitation>
); hyphal system dimitic, with generative hyphae hyaline, thin-walled, septate (
<figureCitation box="[1320,1407,1489,1513]" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="6.[169,232,1980,2000]" captionTargetBox="[171,1412,187,1931]" captionTargetId="figure-13@6.[169,1419,184,1933]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figure 4. Microscopic structures (generative hyphae - left; skeletal hyphae - right; basidiospores). A. Fomitiporia apiahyna. B. F. calkinsii. C. F. conyana. D. F. impercepta. E. F. langloisii. F.F. maxonii. G. F.murrillii. H. F.neotropica." pageId="4" pageNumber="327">Fig. 4E</figureCitation>
); skeletal hyphae yellowish, thick-walled, nonseptate (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="6.[169,232,1980,2000]" captionTargetBox="[171,1412,187,1931]" captionTargetId="figure-13@6.[169,1419,184,1933]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figure 4. Microscopic structures (generative hyphae - left; skeletal hyphae - right; basidiospores). A. Fomitiporia apiahyna. B. F. calkinsii. C. F. conyana. D. F. impercepta. E. F. langloisii. F.F. maxonii. G. F.murrillii. H. F.neotropica." pageId="4" pageNumber="327">Fig. 4E</figureCitation>
); basidiospores dextrinoid, globose, hyaline, thickwalled, 6.5–5 × 6–6.2 μm (
<figureCitation box="[1104,1185,1589,1614]" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="6.[169,232,1980,2000]" captionTargetBox="[171,1412,187,1931]" captionTargetId="figure-13@6.[169,1419,184,1933]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figure 4. Microscopic structures (generative hyphae - left; skeletal hyphae - right; basidiospores). A. Fomitiporia apiahyna. B. F. calkinsii. C. F. conyana. D. F. impercepta. E. F. langloisii. F.F. maxonii. G. F.murrillii. H. F.neotropica." pageId="4" pageNumber="327">Fig. 4E</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="327" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="4.[810,1420,1216,1719]" pageId="4" pageNumber="327">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[810,958,1628,1652]" pageId="4" pageNumber="327">Distribution.</emphasis>
This species is known to occur in North America (
<bibRefCitation author="Murrill WA" box="[918,1061,1662,1686]" pageId="4" pageNumber="327" pagination="1 - 72" refId="ref5916" refString="Murrill WA (1907) Polyporaceae. In: North American flora volume 9 (Agaricales) Polyporaceae - Agaricaceae. Part 1. New York Botanical Garden, New York, USA, 1 - 72." type="book chapter" year="1907">Murrill 1907</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Decock C &amp; Figueroa SH &amp; Robledo G &amp; Castillo G" box="[1073,1280,1662,1686]" pageId="4" pageNumber="327" pagination="733 - 752" refId="ref5299" refString="Decock C, Figueroa SH, Robledo G, Castillo G (2007) Fomitiporia punctata (Basidiomycota, Hymenochaetales) and its presumed taxonomic synonyms in America: taxonomy and phylogeny of some species from tropical / subtropical areas. Mycologia 99 (5): 733 - 752. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 15572536.2007.11832537" type="journal article" year="2007">Decock et al. 2007</bibRefCitation>
), and our record, therefore, is first from South America.
</paragraph>
